alism -- tCHAPTER 12 The ‘Volkskörper’ in Fear: Gender, Race and Sexuality in the Weimar Republic -- tCHAPTER 13 Anica Savić Rebac, Olga Freidenberg, Edith Stein: Love in the Time of War -- tCHAPTER 14 Secular Couplings: An Intergenerational Affair with Islam -- tContributors -- tSelect Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Europe, love has been given a prominent place in European self-representations from the Enlightenment onwards. The category of love, stemming from private and personal spheres, was given a public function and used to distinguish European civilisation from others. Contributors to this volume trace historical links and analyse specific connections between the two discourses on love and Europe over the course of the twentieth century, exploring the distinctions made between the public and private, the political and personal. In doing so, this volume develops an innovative historiography that includes such resources as autobiographies, love letters, and cinematic representations, and takes issue with the exclusivity of Eurocentrism. Its contributors put forth hypotheses about the historical pre-eminence of emotions and consider this history as a basis for a non-Eurocentric understanding of new possible European identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aLovezEuropexHistoryy20th century. 0aNational characteristics, European. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aEllena, Liliana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEllena, Liliana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeppert, Alexander C.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeppert, Alexander C.T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/